Mobiles.LongDescription: `oA small `anutria rat `oswims past you searching for higher ground...``
Mobiles.Description: This nutria rat is happy in the swamps of Teche. He must avoid the trapsset by the locals, as well as stay out of thhe way of the hunting parties.While they hunt for larger game, they still take this beast home for itspelt and small amount of meat.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `aA `ocottonmouth `aripples the water as it sways past you.``
Mobiles.Description: The cottonmouth would rather just be left to itself, but it's not afraidof you or anyone else. It's bite is poisonous...not usually deadly...butpainful none the less. It won't trouble you if you keep your distance.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `cA pair of `kyellow eyes`c swims up, followed by the huge swell of its tail!``
Mobiles.Description: This critter is the meanest of all the swamp inhabitants. And the problemis that he doesn't like you! You best hope he can't see you...and you bestkeep it that way!

Mobiles.LongDescription: `dA friendly looking bayou elf is relaxing here.``
Mobiles.Description: Pideaux is a friendly little fellow...he enjoys having some company inthe swamp (aside from the 'gators and nutria rats). He holds many secretsto this place, after all...he's lived here for six centuries.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A little child runs about...oblivious to your intrusion.
Mobiles.Description: This kid of Teche Village seems to be right with the world. They playjust like all kids, and seem to lack for nothing. In fact, their playgroundis the swamps, which, aside from the gators, is a child's dream! I wouldn'ttry to talk with them...these folks are a bit nervous about strangers...

Mobiles.LongDescription: Jean the keeper of the hounds is standing here.
Mobiles.Description: Jean stands here is smelly overalls with a large sack of...well...it looksto be some kind of feed. He looks amiable enough, so he might tell you whatis going on.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A mean 'ol hound dog waits here for the hunt...
Mobiles.Description: Don't mess wit dem 'ol coondawg...they chew you up real fine, i say.You jus go on der, an let dem der houn's be...dey eat you on up likeyou was da dat bes' peice of meat off a da cow...

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man eyes you warily and contemplates your presence.
Mobiles.Description: The man of Teche Village knows little, if any, english. He wonders whyyou have strolled into the village. The place is private, and the peoplehere like it that way. Your intrusion is, quite frankly, unwanted.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Pierre the cook sweats over a large wood cookstove.
Mobiles.Description: Pierre is the local cusinary talent. The community looks to him to whipup the fancy meals that mark celebrations in this area. He is very proudof his work, and he well should be...they are masterpieces.

Mobiles.LongDescription: There is a pretty woman here waiting for an invitation to dance.
Mobiles.Description: This lady is just waiting for a partner to sway about the dancefloor.You seem like a likely canidate...as you are standing like a doofus ona dance floor and...well...not dancing.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `iJacques`b, the leader of Teche Village, is standing here.``
Mobiles.Description: Jacques is a tall and sturdy fellow. He exudes the strength and wisdomthat it takes to lead the people of this swampland village. He is wisebeyond his years, even though he looks to be not very old. Don't expectmuch chat from him...he is a man of few words, and all those words arefrench.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A woman stands here...and looks for assistance as you approach.
Mobiles.Description: This woman of Teche village is not the most beautiful creature you'veever seen, but in her own way...she is attractive. There are no airs puton in this place. They know how to have fun without leaving the comfortsof home. You consider speaking to her...but think better of it.

Rooms.RoomDescription: The ground seems to get a bit soggy here...as you look carefully intothe trees, you notice that the ground gives way to a wetlands. Ahead thereis a break in the trees...a waterway perhaps?

There is a channel of water that runs in a general north and south direction.It has been cleared of stumps and debris by someone... It looks as if this maybe a rather wet "road" of some sort. It seems that where ever the inhabitantsmight be hiding, they used this channel to get there...

The water only seems to be a few feet deep, and wading through it is notdifficult. The cleared area is only a couple of meters across. This makes ita bit dark since light has a hard time filtering through the tight stands ofCypress trees. From the look of the shadows and moss, the bayou is runningnorth and south...and south leads deeper into the swamp...

The bayou continues to the north and south. This place is a bit creepy...one could start wondering what might pop out from behind the old trees.The cacophony of the swamp creatures fills the air...hope they're all fed!

The bayous of the southern swamps can be a treacherous place. It mightbe wise to just stay on the waterway and forgo all prospects of delvinginto the depths of the dark swamp. You might be asking for trouble...somegreat men have lost their way in this place.

The swamp is so full of life it is hard to fathom why you see such littleaction. There is plenty to be heard, but aside from the few fearless ones,the creatures stay well hidden. Are they frightened at your intrusion inparticular? Or are they just well hunted....

There seems to be a small break in the tight stand of trees to the east,as if something tracks that way. A shortcut? perhaps...might be some finehunting off in that direction. Or, you might end up AS some fine hunting!You can stay with the safety of the main track...might be for the best.

The watery corridor continues to the north and south. Some considerationmust be taken to have proper supplies if you intend to venture in thisland. The water is unfit to drink, and hunting the beasts which residein the area might be difficult if you lack the skills particular to thearea...you could look up the locals...if you can find them!

The way to the north is dark and forboding...but then, the whole PLACEis that way. At least to the south it seems to lighten a bit, and thereis an area that seems a bit wider. Maybe there is some kind of exit fromthis dreadful place...

The bayous of Terrebonne and Lafourche form a junction here. There mustbe more than one way out of the swamp, but from this vantage, there isn'ta clear direction to choose. If your lucky enough to have a gold piece,you might flip it and decide on a direction! But don't drop it...

The tree lined channel seems very confining. Although it seems that theland to the west is a bit higher and might be drier, there is no pass togain access. There are sounds coming from that direction, but it is hardto tell if the sounds are human in nature...or just nature itself.

The wet passage continues north and south. But to the south, it looks as ifthe end is in sight. There is also some type of structure in that direction.It might be a way out of the knee deep water and soggy bottomed bayou. Theground seems a bit higher to the west, but no clear pass through the treesis evident.

The cleared waterway dead ends here. The bayou runs north and in all otherdirections there is only swamp...except to the west. There is a rickety olddock that just might hold a persons weight. It looks as if it might lead tosolid ground...so what the heck!

The eastern end of Bayou Terrebonne gets a bit deeper than the otherportions of the swamp. This area may have been dredged a bit for reasonsunknown. Aside from giants and the like, travellers are up to their waistat this point. These cleared passages were definitely intended for boatsof some type or another.

The monotony of the swamp passage is broken here by a small break in thecolumns of trees which deter any travel into the heart of the swamp. Thequestion may be wether anyone would want to venture into the dark unknownof the marsh. The hearty adventurer might take the challenge...others mayjust decide to press onward.

The watery passage continues east and west.  The going isn't too rough inthis area.  The critters who call this place home are either friendly orscared of your intrusion.  You might consider coming here to do a bit ofhunting...  But you might want a guide if you intend to venture past theconfines of the tree lined bayou.

The bayou continues to the east and west. There is some commotion to thesouth, but it seems like a rough trip to head that direction. And besides,who knows what's making that commotion! You may find a way...if you lookaround.

Although the only way to travel is along the east and west bayou, youcan see the ground to the south rises above the water level of the swamp.Ahead to the west, there is a wider area which might afford a passage todry ground. There is also some signs of life...human life.

The wooded area to the east gives way to the swampy area of the bayou. Theway west is cleared of the Cypress trees, but is still covered in stagnentwater. Off to the east, there seems to be a well worn track through the trees.It is almost as if this way is some kind of well used route by travelers. Youonly wonder where the boats might be stored...

The spanish moss is thick upon the grand old Cypress trees that grow kneedeep in the water here. You turn about, looking up at the magestic sight...Whoa! Which way did you come from? All these trees look alike! You might trycalling for help...but there is no telling who, or what, might answer yourcall.
It certainly was easy to get lost in this place. Even with a map, findingyour way will be difficult. The eerie sounds of the wild animals seem to becoming from all directions. Which way is out?

Rooms.TpMsg: As you step out of the maze-like swamp, you find yourself on dry ground.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Finally! A dry place to stand. In fact, up on this wide stump, you can seequite a bit more than from ground (or water) level. A couple of bayous arevisible from here. This might also be a nice place to catch your breath andrest up before you journey any further.

This is the western end of the channel. The reason it comes to an endis because this is where the locals pull their boats onto the ground.To the south, these boats lay scattered about where the dry ground risesabove the slow moving water of the swamp.

Among the oddly shaped boats, the earth changes from muck, to mire, andfinally to somewhat solid footing. A sandy path leads to the south awayfrom the bayou. All around the cypress trees rise high above ground level.Any expedition other than the obvious would be a mighty undertaking.

It is evident that no one took the time to actually clear this path.The winding nature leads a person to believe that this trail has beenbeaten down with use. Off to the southwest you can hear some sounds oflife.

It is evident that no one took the time to actually clear this path.The winding nature leads a person to believe that this trail has beenbeaten down with use. Off to the southwest you can hear some sounds oflife.

The pathway begins to widen, and to the south the edge of a clearingbecomes visible.  There is no sound from the northwest, but to the east thesilence is occassionally broken.  There is also a faint smell of food beingprepared.

The edge of the clearing doesn't afford much of a view. The sandy pathto the north is very tight, but the clearing widens a bit to the east.There are some inhabitants of the village milling about, they tend toshy away from you, being a stranger. But they can be seen in the shadowsfrom the corner of an eye...
The middle of the clearing affords two general directions, east, whichseems to wind off into the trees. And west, which looks as if it leads tothe more populated area of the village.

The smaller clearing to the west gives way to the main track of thevillage which runs north and south.  To the north, there are a coupleclapboard shacks which look well cared for, despite the obvious poverty.Off to the south, you see what must amount to the village center, andbeyond, a larger single story building.

It is surprising how well tended the small homes that surround you arekept. Although the village seems quite poor, the pride in the communitythat they have carved from this swamp is well in evidence. There is quitea bit of pride and tender care put into the creation of the tiny shanties.The buildings to the north and west seem to be dwellings, and to the east,a smaller structure stands locked.

This looks to be the central gathering place of the village.  Downed logsencircle a small fire that heats a large kettle of water.  It could be thewater supply for the small community.  In any case, at a slow boil, it seemsfit for consumption...  Hope its okay to have a drink.

South of the village center there is a low, slat sided building. Itseems to be larger than any other building in the village. It could bethe indoor meeting place of the community. In any case, the place looksinviting, and who knows what you might find!

There is a fishing dock to the east, and it looks like the center of thevillage is west of here. The ground is soft but solid, and the villageseems like a freindly place. You might need an interpreter, tho...

The old dock seems to be built a bit better than it looks. There aren'tany boats tied here, so this might be a spot where the locals fish...orcatch whatever seafood they might find. The bayou to the east might holdany type of water creature imaginable. Of to the west, there is a village.

The western edge of the gathering place tapers off into a small area.The trees still command most of the view, and when the space between them istight, they seem to encompass the entire view.  The spanish moss grows sothickly that it is difficult to see into the woodlands.  A small trail leadsoff to the west.

This path that winds over exposed roots and around trees leads awayfrom the main village to the west, and deeper into the woodland swamp tothe south. Athough sounds are muted by the vegetation, there is a distinctsound of animals to the southwest.

The path ends here, being quite short after all. There is a small areafrom which the trees and brush have been cleared, and old fencing is tackedto the trees, making a small pen. To the west, the gate to the pen is shutand held with a small tie. Your nose crinkles at the odor eminating fromthe structure, and you hear low growls...

Whew! What a nasty place! A broken down fenced pen that barely keepsin the dogs. And you can be sure they love getting out! The place is fleainfested, covered in fecal matter, and swarming with all types of insects.These animals can not be happy...

The seemingly small building looks a bit larger once a person comesinside. But it's the smell of the creole fare being prepared that onenotices first. Off to the west, there is a kitchen of sorts with alltypes of cauldrons and cooking gear for creating fabulous creations.You might be tempted to head that way if your at all hungry. If dancingis your thing, the east side of the building have a wide open dance floorwhere the villagers cavort to the local music.

Yes indeed! This is where the smells of the fine cuisine are eminating.There a pots and pans covering the place, some boiling and some simmering.It looks as if the entire village eats here most of the time. And on thisoccasion, it looks as if there is a feast in preparation. I'll bet youcould impose and sit in on this one!

Well...this certainly is the nicest floor in the village. It looks to bemade from the local hardwood, but the polishing has been done by the manybarefoot dancers that have swept to and fro. There is a small stage wherethe local zydeco band plays. The hometown music is quite different thanany you may have heard before.

What a cozy place! The one room domicile has all the creature comforts.There is a stone fireplace with a large hearth, and all the utensils neededto whip up a meal. The wood framed bed looks quite inviting. If you weresure you wouldn't be disturbed, you might consider a nap! The hand madearticles that fill the place make you think that the lifestyle here mightnot be so bad after all...

This one-room home is a bit larger than the others aroung the villageit seems that a family lives here. There are several beds and the firepit is much larger. The place doesn't have many items which are notdirectly tied to everyday life. The existence here must be very simple.

This shack is used by the entire community as a common area to storegoods to be used by all. There are many items that are used for huntingand fishing. There are crab and crawfish nets by the dozens, boatingsupplies, and some traps. This also seems to be the spot where any of thevillage weaponry is kept.

Whew! what a tight fit...It's hard to believe anything can fit in this tinyspace. Let's hope the prize was worth the effort, because you could verywell end up stuck in here. The hole is musky and damp, with roots poking atyour sides. Now...see if you can back on out of this burrow!

As you step onto the sandbar, your feet sink slightly into the ground,and you wonder nervously if it will hold you.  This strip of land separatesthe wastelands of the swamp and the pure body of water that sparkles to thenorth.
You stand at the very tip of a sandbar.  Waves from the sapphire sea tothe north lap up against the sand, making parts of it wet and clumpy.  Tothe south, the scent of swampland permeates the air.
